00:36:04.508 --> 00:36:08.228
It's my pleasure to introduce Michael Berger from Memorial Sloan

610
00:36:08.288 --> 00:36:09.528
Kettering, and

611
00:36:10.768 --> 00:36:13.908
he'll be talking about sequencing to treatment, the role of AI in precision

612
00:36:13.968 --> 00:36:14.528
oncology.

613
00:36:16.364 --> 00:36:19.544
Thank you so much. I'm really excited to be here, and to all of you for

614
00:36:19.924 --> 00:36:23.424
attending. I know it's so nice outside and we're happy that you're here with us

615
00:36:23.464 --> 00:36:23.584
here.

616
00:36:24.804 --> 00:36:28.414
So my name is Mike Berger. I'm at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center,

617
00:36:28.684 --> 00:36:32.654
and I have the privilege of describing some of the ways

618
00:36:32.724 --> 00:36:36.384
that we've begun to incorporate and think about incorporating AI

619
00:36:36.404 --> 00:36:39.004
methods into our clinical genomics workflows.

620
00:36:39.864 --> 00:36:43.524
So I want to first start by defining to you what I think of when I say

621
00:36:43.664 --> 00:36:44.924
clinical genomics workflow.

622
00:36:45.804 --> 00:36:49.754
And in precision oncology, it typically involves taking DNA from

623
00:36:49.764 --> 00:36:53.313
the tumor and sometimes match normal cells or tissues from patients with

624
00:36:53.344 --> 00:36:57.304
cancer, creating libraries that we can then select for genes of

625
00:36:57.344 --> 00:37:00.494
interest, either with amplification or hybridization,

626
00:37:01.184 --> 00:37:04.324
in panels, but could also be whole exome or whole genome

627
00:37:04.364 --> 00:37:07.904
sequencing, where we would then sequence these samples to high

628
00:37:08.004 --> 00:37:11.764
coverage to detect mutations, copy number alterations, rearrangements,

629
00:37:12.624 --> 00:37:16.354
individual alterations that could then be annotated for their biological

630
00:37:16.424 --> 00:37:20.344
significance, for their clinical significance, and use this information

631
00:37:20.404 --> 00:37:23.064
to guide the treatment decisions for patients with cancer.

632
00:37:23.864 --> 00:37:27.734
We've been doing this at Sloan Kettering now for about 13 years with

633
00:37:27.734 --> 00:37:31.644
next-generation sequencing, for probably close to 20 or more

634
00:37:31.684 --> 00:37:32.904
years with

635
00:37:34.104 --> 00:37:35.904
other mutation profiling approaches.

636
00:37:35.964 --> 00:37:39.944
But AI methods have now improved enough that there are

637
00:37:40.124 --> 00:37:42.364
real opportunities to incorporate

638
00:37:43.964 --> 00:37:47.624
into our workflows, either for efficiency or for more

639
00:37:47.704 --> 00:37:51.664
accuracy or more sensitivity, particularly in the areas of variant

640
00:37:51.684 --> 00:37:52.154
detection,

641
00:37:52.984 --> 00:37:55.924
variant interpretation, and clinical decision support.

642
00:37:56.844 --> 00:38:00.684
And I also want to highlight a few additional applications that can leverage

643
00:38:00.724 --> 00:38:02.464
these clinical genomics

644
00:38:03.324 --> 00:38:06.604
workflows beyond just mutation-guided treatment selection,

645
00:38:07.604 --> 00:38:11.404
such as cancer type diagnosis, monitoring and early detection of

646
00:38:11.444 --> 00:38:14.424
cancer using liquid biopsy approaches, and

647
00:38:15.024 --> 00:38:15.884
developing models

648
00:38:16.764 --> 00:38:20.644
using real-world data and evidence to predict outcomes.

649
00:38:21.284 --> 00:38:23.984
So this is essentially the outline of this talk today.

650
00:38:24.784 --> 00:38:28.104
So I'll go through each of these categories and highlight some ways that AI methods

651
00:38:28.124 --> 00:38:29.844
and tools are making a difference.

652
00:38:30.724 --> 00:38:34.634
So first, with detection of genomic alterations, current practice, at least

653
00:38:34.664 --> 00:38:38.144
for us, still involves probabilistic base mutation callers.

654
00:38:38.204 --> 00:38:41.984
So using the allele counts for mutant and

655
00:38:42.024 --> 00:38:45.824
wild type alleles to detect mutations, as well as base qualities and mapping

656
00:38:45.864 --> 00:38:47.524
qualities and strand bias,

657
00:38:49.304 --> 00:38:51.364
to derive a probability

658
00:38:52.984 --> 00:38:56.604
score that we could apply thresholds to and call mutations.

659
00:38:57.124 --> 00:39:00.834
Copy number pipelines typically use coverage, sometimes with SNP allele

660
00:39:00.924 --> 00:39:04.884
frequencies, and we've certainly used this to great effect

661
00:39:04.924 --> 00:39:08.564
at Sloan Kettering. So just a quick word about our clinical sequencing test.

662
00:39:08.624 --> 00:39:12.504
We've been running MSK-IMPACT as our tumor normal 500 gene

663
00:39:12.604 --> 00:39:15.444
panel for patients with cancer for now about 13 years.

664
00:39:16.404 --> 00:39:20.364
We use both tumor and normal to distinguish between

665
00:39:20.404 --> 00:39:23.524
somatic mutations, germline variants, and clonal hematopoiesis

666
00:39:23.564 --> 00:39:27.364
mutations. And so far, we've sequenced over 100,000 patients with this

667
00:39:27.404 --> 00:39:31.304
test, over 140,000 tumors, and which this data set has allowed us,

668
00:39:31.364 --> 00:39:35.264
with high precision, to identify the frequencies of mutations across different

669
00:39:35.304 --> 00:39:38.864
types of cancers, not just even general cancer types, but more

670
00:39:38.904 --> 00:39:42.584
granular subtypes as well. And we've been able to supplement these

671
00:39:42.644 --> 00:39:46.104
alterations detected clinically with additional, more complex

672
00:39:46.184 --> 00:39:50.004
features and signatures and mutation properties to further enrich

673
00:39:50.044 --> 00:39:53.724
these data sets. And just as a quick mention, our largest public

674
00:39:53.764 --> 00:39:57.304
release was just published earlier this month in "Cancer Cell," if you want to take

675
00:39:57.364 --> 00:39:57.924
a deeper look.

676
00:40:00.104 --> 00:40:03.964
Even within these conventional pipelines, there are significant opportunities

677
00:40:04.004 --> 00:40:07.784
for AI. So using error modeling to identify artifacts

678
00:40:08.584 --> 00:40:11.704
beyond the conventional thresholds that are used.

679
00:40:12.504 --> 00:40:16.484
AI-assisted QC and variant review for greater efficiency, given that this is

680
00:40:16.544 --> 00:40:20.284
a significant bottleneck in our ability

681
00:40:20.344 --> 00:40:24.204
to turn around the volume of tests that we perform in a

682
00:40:24.244 --> 00:40:24.864
rapid manner.

683
00:40:25.924 --> 00:40:29.684
And then, especially for labs that do tumor-only sequencing without the match

684
00:40:29.694 --> 00:40:30.024
normal,

685
00:40:30.964 --> 00:40:34.344
applying AI methods to infer which of the variants detected in the

686
00:40:34.424 --> 00:40:35.284
tumor are

687
00:40:36.344 --> 00:40:40.124
specific to the tumor versus inherited germline variants or

688
00:40:40.364 --> 00:40:44.304
clonal hematopoiesis mutations in infiltrating lymphocytes, or

689
00:40:44.384 --> 00:40:45.924
in liquid biopsy assays,

690
00:40:47.264 --> 00:40:50.604
mutations that are detected in cell-free DNA, which is particularly challenging

691
00:40:50.644 --> 00:40:54.504
given that the primary component of cell-free DNA is derived from hematopoietic

692
00:40:54.524 --> 00:40:58.164
cells. So here's one example of a tool.

693
00:40:58.414 --> 00:41:02.304
This was published by AstraZeneca last year called MetaCH that performed

694
00:41:02.364 --> 00:41:06.294
this last task of training on our MSK-IMPACT tumor match normal

695
00:41:06.384 --> 00:41:10.244
data to infer in a liquid biopsy test whether a given variant was

696
00:41:10.284 --> 00:41:13.504
likely to be somatic or associated with clonal hematopoiesis.

697
00:41:15.664 --> 00:41:19.204
But the methods for calling mutations have also fundamentally changed.

698
00:41:19.284 --> 00:41:21.964
So this is actually not even that new at this point.

699
00:41:22.544 --> 00:41:26.344
There's a whole new class of mutation callers that can

700
00:41:26.424 --> 00:41:30.414
learn patterns directly from the raw data and essentially turn mutation calling

701
00:41:30.464 --> 00:41:32.864
into an image analysis and recognition problem.

702
00:41:32.904 --> 00:41:35.684
So Deep Variant is one of the first of these methods, which

703
00:41:35.744 --> 00:41:39.664
was actually now 10 years ago, shown to have

704
00:41:39.684 --> 00:41:43.524
the highest performance in the 2016 PrecisionFDA Truth Challenge and

705
00:41:43.544 --> 00:41:46.664
performed particularly well for difficult to map regions.

706
00:41:46.984 --> 00:41:50.544
This was for germline variant calling, and I guess the way, in general, these

707
00:41:50.584 --> 00:41:54.444
methods work is they can take the read pile-ups, turn it into an

708
00:41:54.504 --> 00:41:58.284
image or other machine-readable representation, and then with convolutional neural

709
00:41:58.324 --> 00:42:02.244
networks trained on large data sets with ground truth, predict the

710
00:42:02.284 --> 00:42:03.904
likelihood that a given

711
00:42:05.304 --> 00:42:07.964
read pile-up is representing a mutation.

712
00:42:08.424 --> 00:42:12.404
So this was first used for germline variant detection, but more recently has

713
00:42:12.424 --> 00:42:16.274
been adapted for somatic calling through methods like new somatic and

714
00:42:16.284 --> 00:42:19.876
deep somatic.And the kind of

715
00:42:19.896 --> 00:42:23.536
information that we try to infer from the data goes often beyond the

716
00:42:23.576 --> 00:42:25.316
presence of individual alterations.

717
00:42:25.396 --> 00:42:28.856
So there are certain mutational signatures or other

718
00:42:28.956 --> 00:42:32.916
genomic features that can have importance both biologically

719
00:42:32.956 --> 00:42:36.736
and clinically. And AI-based signature detection can be

720
00:42:36.876 --> 00:42:40.836
used because it's optimally suited to learn complex high-dimensional patterns.

721
00:42:40.916 --> 00:42:44.856
So, one example of this being microsatellite instability, many of you may

722
00:42:44.916 --> 00:42:48.216
know this is a genomic signature that's highly predictive of response to

723
00:42:48.256 --> 00:42:51.865
immunotherapy and can be detected based on variable length insertions and

724
00:42:52.056 --> 00:42:53.685
deletions at microsatellite sites.

725
00:42:54.216 --> 00:42:57.886
AI methods can now use that integrated with somatic variants,

726
00:42:57.996 --> 00:43:01.376
insertions, deletions, and sequence contexts.

727
00:43:01.456 --> 00:43:05.136
And I'm showing here one example of a tool called myMSI that was developed by

728
00:43:05.176 --> 00:43:08.776
colleagues at Sloan Kettering, that we've begun to perform

729
00:43:08.816 --> 00:43:11.326
alongside our conventional method, MSI Sensor.

730
00:43:11.796 --> 00:43:14.846
And it's actually shown to have better performance and result in fewer

731
00:43:14.876 --> 00:43:17.816
indeterminate cases where we're unable to derive a result.

732
00:43:18.876 --> 00:43:22.176
Another example being homologous recombination deficiency.

733
00:43:22.185 --> 00:43:24.856
This is a signature representing a different type of DNA

734
00:43:25.736 --> 00:43:29.416
repair defect that is often detected through genomic

735
00:43:29.516 --> 00:43:33.416
scars, like widespread loss of heterozygosity and telomeric allele counterbalance

736
00:43:33.456 --> 00:43:36.556
and state transitions in the genome.

737
00:43:37.146 --> 00:43:40.256
But also can leverage additional patterns through single nucleotide variants,

738
00:43:40.336 --> 00:43:41.586
indels, and structural variants.

739
00:43:42.276 --> 00:43:46.116
And I'm showing here an example called Sigma, developed by Peter Park's group at

740
00:43:46.136 --> 00:43:49.056
Harvard Medical School that can actually infer,

741
00:43:50.716 --> 00:43:54.146
and adapt signatures based on larger whole genome and exome data,

742
00:43:54.796 --> 00:43:58.016
down to smaller numbers of mutations inferred in panels.

743
00:43:58.476 --> 00:44:02.096
So these are important tools that have immediate clinical

744
00:44:02.106 --> 00:44:05.416
potential to inform treatment decisions.

745
00:44:06.816 --> 00:44:10.056
So then once we've detected alterations, I'm reverting back now to

746
00:44:10.096 --> 00:44:12.666
individual genomic alterations like mutations.

747
00:44:12.956 --> 00:44:16.076
We want to ask, "Well, which of the mutations that we detected are likely

748
00:44:16.176 --> 00:44:20.116
functional?" And this currently relies on databases,

749
00:44:20.476 --> 00:44:23.476
population frequency, a little different for somatic and germline.

750
00:44:23.536 --> 00:44:27.526
So for somatic mutation, we use evidence of recurrence across different tumors as

751
00:44:27.556 --> 00:44:31.536
an indicator of selective pressures that suggest that the mutation is

752
00:44:31.556 --> 00:44:32.416
functionally important.

753
00:44:33.436 --> 00:44:37.376
For germline variants, usually common variants can be recognized as

754
00:44:37.416 --> 00:44:40.816
likely benign or of minimal significance.

755
00:44:42.236 --> 00:44:46.016
But also epidemiological studies, family studies, functional studies, any

756
00:44:46.036 --> 00:44:48.036
information that we can leverage.

757
00:44:48.756 --> 00:44:52.656
There are a number of databases now of both somatic mutations and germline

758
00:44:52.696 --> 00:44:56.496
variants that help us infer whether a new variant that we detect in a given

759
00:44:56.556 --> 00:44:58.436
patient is likely functional.

760
00:44:59.636 --> 00:45:02.616
And there have also been a number of guidelines published for how to

761
00:45:03.656 --> 00:45:07.356
actually interpret a given somatic or a given germline

762
00:45:07.416 --> 00:45:10.455
variant, usually based on rules of what kind of evidence would

763
00:45:10.516 --> 00:45:11.556
qualify

764
00:45:13.996 --> 00:45:14.236
to

765
00:45:15.056 --> 00:45:17.836
call a mutation as pathogenic or not.

766
00:45:17.896 --> 00:45:21.645
And the framework is similar but slightly different between germline and

767
00:45:21.696 --> 00:45:25.556
somatic mutations. For germline, there's a five-tiered system that goes

768
00:45:25.596 --> 00:45:29.506
from benign and likely benign to pathogenic or likely pathogenic, meaning that

769
00:45:29.576 --> 00:45:33.376
that variant is associated with the onset or incidence of cancer.

770
00:45:33.436 --> 00:45:36.816
And for somatic mutations, typically we call it benign or likely benign or

771
00:45:36.876 --> 00:45:40.746
oncogenic or likely oncogenic, suggesting that that mutation is important

772
00:45:40.776 --> 00:45:43.456
for the ongoing tumor genesis progression of cancer.

773
00:45:46.536 --> 00:45:47.496
And there have been methods

774
00:45:48.336 --> 00:45:51.736
trained on these large databases of known functional

775
00:45:51.836 --> 00:45:55.716
variants that have been used to develop, in these

776
00:45:55.756 --> 00:45:59.536
cases, largely random forest models predicting the functional

777
00:45:59.576 --> 00:46:02.756
consequences of both somatic and germline variants.

778
00:46:02.796 --> 00:46:05.456
And I'm showing a number of examples here, and some of you

779
00:46:06.276 --> 00:46:07.536
may be very familiar with these.

780
00:46:08.416 --> 00:46:12.396
But we've sort of entered a new era of deep learning where neural

781
00:46:12.456 --> 00:46:16.336
networks can be assembled, leveraging some of this information, as

782
00:46:16.376 --> 00:46:18.556
well as, in the case of AlphaMisSense,

783
00:46:19.516 --> 00:46:20.816
which is based on AlphaFold,

784
00:46:22.336 --> 00:46:25.636
protein structural information along with evolutionary conservation.

785
00:46:26.316 --> 00:46:30.016
So AlphaMisSense a few years ago was released by Google

786
00:46:30.116 --> 00:46:32.096
DeepMind as a way to predict

787
00:46:32.896 --> 00:46:35.156
the pathogenicity of missense variants.

788
00:46:35.796 --> 00:46:39.736
Splice AI is a tool from Illumina that can infer splicing

789
00:46:39.776 --> 00:46:43.456
from pre-mRNA sequence and identify splice junctions

790
00:46:43.496 --> 00:46:47.356
and therefore identify the likely consequences of splicing on individual

791
00:46:47.416 --> 00:46:48.436
missense mutations.

792
00:46:49.256 --> 00:46:52.796
And then, most recently, AlphaGenome, kind of a follow-on to

793
00:46:52.836 --> 00:46:56.676
AlphaMisSense, was released by Google DeepMind earlier this year, that

794
00:46:56.736 --> 00:47:00.356
can take large stretches of non-coding sequence and infer at base pair

795
00:47:00.396 --> 00:47:04.376
resolution the likelihood of changes that impact chromosomal accessibility,

796
00:47:04.476 --> 00:47:08.126
transcription factor binding, splicing, expression, and many other

797
00:47:08.136 --> 00:47:11.976
genomic tracks. So this is all happening very quickly, but tools that we

798
00:47:12.016 --> 00:47:13.446
can take full advantage of.

799
00:47:15.356 --> 00:47:15.986
All right. So now,

800
00:47:16.896 --> 00:47:20.866
the next step beyond inferring the likely functional significance of mutation is

801
00:47:20.876 --> 00:47:24.796
determining whether there are clinical implications for a patient's treatment when

802
00:47:24.836 --> 00:47:28.656
we see those mutations. What's the clinical actionability of the mutations that we

803
00:47:28.696 --> 00:47:32.076
find? And this, I think, still relies largely on

804
00:47:32.136 --> 00:47:34.596
